    content: `<h2 id="video-guide">Watch: 99% of Beginners Don't Know the Basics of AI</h2><p>In this video, a seasoned AI enthusiast breaks down the five key takeaways from Google's AI Essentials course — a \$49 investment that reveals the foundational knowledge most beginners miss. From understanding the three types of AI tools to mastering prompt engineering, this video is a goldmine for anyone looking to leverage AI effectively in business.</p><div class="not-prose my-8 aspect-video overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 shadow-lg"><iframe class="h-full w-full" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/nVyD6THcvDQ" title="99% of Beginners Don't Know the Basics of AI" loading="lazy" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe></div><h2 id="intro">Introduction: Why AI Basics Matter More Than Ever</h2><p>Last week, I watched a video that has already racked up over 3.3 million views — and for good reason. The creator spent 5 hours and \$49 on Google's AI Essentials course and distilled it into five takeaways that every beginner (and even some experienced users) needs to hear. The video is packed with practical advice, but what struck me most is how many of the lessons directly apply to the way businesses can — and should — be using AI today.</p><p>As a senior tech blogger for Dooza.ai, I see companies every day struggling with the same problems: too many emails, too much manual research, and not enough hours in the day. The video's insights are a perfect starting point, but the real magic happens when you pair that knowledge with the right tools. That's where Dooza's AI employees come in — but more on that later.</p><h2 id="takeaway-1">Takeaway #1: The Three Types of AI Tools</h2><p>The video breaks down AI tools into three categories: <strong>standalone tools</strong> (like ChatGPT, Gemini, and Midjourney), <strong>tools with integrated AI features</strong> (like Google Docs with Gemini built in), and <strong>custom AI solutions</strong> (like Johns Hopkins' sepsis detection system).</p><p>This is a crucial distinction because it helps you understand where to invest your time and money. Standalone tools are great for one-off tasks, but they require you to constantly switch contexts. Integrated features are convenient, but they lock you into a specific ecosystem. Custom solutions are powerful, but they often require significant technical expertise to build and maintain.</p><p>Here's where Dooza's approach stands out. Instead of forcing you to choose between these categories, Dooza offers <strong>pre-built AI employees</strong> that are essentially custom solutions designed for common business tasks — without the technical overhead. For example, <strong>Maily</strong> is your email and customer support AI, <strong>Somi</strong> handles social media, <strong>Ranky</strong> takes care of SEO, and <strong>Stan</strong> manages leads. These are not just standalone tools; they are purpose-built AI employees that integrate seamlessly into your workflow.</p><h2 id="takeaway-2">Takeaway #2: Surface the Implied Context</h2><p>The video's second lesson is a prompt engineering gem: always surface the implied context. The example given is a vegetarian friend asking for restaurant recommendations — you instinctively know to suggest vegetarian options, but an AI doesn't. You have to explicitly state that context.</p><p>This is a common pitfall for beginners. They assume the AI knows what they know. But the reality is that AI models are incredibly literal. If you're asking for a sales email, you need to include details like your target audience, the product's unique selling points, and the desired tone. Otherwise, you'll get generic, low-quality output.</p><p>At Dooza, we've baked this principle into our AI employees. When you set up <strong>Stan</strong> for lead generation, you provide context once — your industry, ideal customer profile, and messaging guidelines — and Stan uses that context every time it reaches out to a prospect. No need to re-explain yourself. Similarly, <strong>Maily</strong> learns your brand voice and customer history, so every email response is personalized and on-brand.</p><h2 id="takeaway-3">Takeaway #3: Zero-Shot vs. Few-Shot Prompting</h2><p>The video explains that "shot" refers to the number of examples you provide in a prompt. Zero-shot means no examples, one-shot means one example, and few-shot means two or more. The more relevant examples you give, the better the output.</p><p>This is a powerful technique, but it can be time-consuming to craft the perfect few-shot prompt every time. That's why Dooza's AI employees come pre-trained with thousands of examples from real-world business scenarios. For instance, <strong>Somi</strong> doesn't need you to show it examples of good social media posts — it already knows what works for your industry. <strong>Ranky</strong> understands SEO best practices without you having to provide a list of keywords and backlink strategies. The few-shot learning is built into the system, so you get expert-level output with zero effort.</p><h2 id="takeaway-4">Takeaway #4: Chain of Thought Prompting</h2><p>Chain of thought prompting is about breaking a complex task into smaller, manageable steps. The video uses the example of writing a cover letter: instead of asking the AI to write the whole thing at once, you ask for a hook, then a body paragraph, then a closing. This leads to much better results.</p><p>This is a fantastic technique for one-off tasks, but for recurring business processes, you want something more automated. Dooza's AI employees are designed to handle multi-step workflows without you having to micromanage. For example, <strong>Maily</strong> can handle a customer support ticket from initial triage to resolution, escalating only when necessary. <strong>Stan</strong> can manage an entire lead nurturing sequence — from initial outreach to follow-up to scheduling a demo — all without you having to break it down step by step.</p><h2 id="takeaway-5">Takeaway #5: Understand AI Limitations</h2><p>The video highlights three main limitations: biased training data, insufficient information on recent topics, and hallucinations (factually incorrect outputs). The creator notes that hallucinations can sometimes be a feature (e.g., for brainstorming), but they're usually a bug.</p><p>This is where Dooza's AI employees truly shine. Because they are purpose-built for specific tasks, they are trained on high-quality, domain-specific data. <strong>Maily</strong> won't hallucinate a refund policy because it's been trained on your actual policies. <strong>Ranky</strong> won't recommend outdated SEO tactics because it's constantly updated with the latest best practices. And all Dooza AI employees have built-in guardrails to minimize bias and ensure accuracy.</p><h2 id="dooza-solution">How Dooza’s AI Employees Solve These Problems</h2><p>The video's insights are invaluable, but they also highlight a gap: knowing the basics is one thing, but implementing them at scale is another. That's where Dooza comes in.</p><p>Dooza provides a suite of AI employees that are ready to work for your business 24/7, without breaks, without complaints, and without the need for constant prompt engineering. Here's how each one addresses the challenges discussed in the video:</p><ul><li><strong>Maily</strong> — Your email and customer support AI. Handles tickets, answers queries, and manages inbox overload. No more implied context issues — Maily learns your business inside out.</li><li><strong>Somi</strong> — Your social media AI. Creates, schedules, and posts content that resonates. Few-shot prompting is built in, so you get high-quality posts without the trial and error.</li><li><strong>Ranky</strong> — Your SEO AI. Optimizes your content, tracks rankings, and suggests improvements. Chain of thought? Ranky handles the entire SEO workflow from keyword research to on-page optimization.</li><li><strong>Stan</strong> — Your lead generation AI. Finds, qualifies, and nurtures leads. Stan surfaces the implied context of your ideal customer and uses few-shot examples to craft perfect outreach.</li></ul><p>And because Dooza's AI employees are custom solutions, they avoid the limitations of generic AI tools. No hallucinations, no biased outputs, no outdated data — just reliable, accurate automation.</p><h2 id="cta">Ready to Automate Your Business with AI?</h2><div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1a6b7a, #2a9d5c); border-radius: 16px; padding: 40px; text-align: center; margin: 32px 0;"><h3 style="color: white; font-size: 24px; margin: 0 0 12px;">Ready to automate your business with AI?</h3><p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9); font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 24px;">Book a free consultation with our team and see how Dooza's AI employees can work for you.</p><a href="https://dooza.ai/book" style="display: inline-block; background: white; color: #1a6b7a; padding: 14px 32px; border-radius: 8px; text-decoration: none; font-weight: 700; font-size: 16px;">Book a Free Meeting</a></div><h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2><h3>What are the three types of AI tools mentioned in Google's course?</h3><p>Standalone tools (e.g., ChatGPT, Midjourney), tools with integrated AI features (e.g., Google Docs with Gemini), and custom AI solutions (e.g., Johns Hopkins' sepsis detection system).</p><h3>How can Dooza's AI employees help with customer support?</h3><p>Dooza's AI employees like Maily handle emails and customer tickets 24/7 without breaks, ensuring fast, accurate responses and freeing up your human team.</p><h3>What is chain-of-thought prompting?</h3><p>It's a technique where you break a complex task into smaller, manageable steps to help AI models produce more accurate and consistent results.</p>`
