    content: `<h2 id="introduction">Introduction: The Viral Lie That’s Hurting the Industry</h2><p>If you’ve spent any time on YouTube lately, you’ve probably seen them: teenagers in hoodies claiming they’re making \$200,000 to \$300,000 a month selling AI automations to businesses. They flash screenshots of Stripe dashboards, promise you can do the same in weeks, and then ask you to buy their course or join their newsletter.</p><p>It sounds too good to be true—because it is.</p><p>In a brutally honest video that has racked up over 360,000 views, a seasoned AI agency owner (who wishes to remain anonymous) finally calls out the lies. He’s been running an AI agency for over a year, has a growing YouTube channel, and has actually made money—over \$100,000 total. But here’s the kicker: most of that came from teaching people, not from selling automations. His actual agency revenue? A peak of \$30,000 in one month, with an average of \$10,000 to \$15,000.</p><p>He’s not alone. The vast majority of honest AI automation professionals earn far less than the viral gurus claim. And the damage these false promises cause is real: they discourage genuine entrepreneurs, erode trust in the industry, and make it harder for legitimate businesses to sell real value.</p><p>In this post, we’ll break down the key insights from that video, add our own analysis, and show you how to build a sustainable AI automation business—or simply automate your own operations—using proven tools like <strong>Dooza.ai</strong>, which offers specialized AI employees for email, social media, SEO, and lead generation.</p><h2 id="video-guide">Watch: The TRUTH About Selling AI Automations to Businesses</h2><p>Before we dive deeper, watch the video that sparked this conversation. It’s a must-watch for anyone considering an AI automation agency or looking to hire one.</p><div class="not-prose my-8 aspect-video overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 shadow-lg"><iframe class="h-full w-full" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/XUYvDbAv1IA" title="The TRUTH About Selling AI Automations to Businesses" loading="lazy" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe></div><h2 id="the-real-numbers">The Real Numbers: What an Honest Agency Owner Actually Earns</h2><p>The video creator is refreshingly transparent. He shares his own numbers:</p><ul><li><strong>Total revenue from his AI agency over a year:</strong> Over \$100,000 (but mostly from teaching, not client work).</li><li><strong>Best month from client automations:</strong> \$30,000.</li><li><strong>Average monthly revenue from his consultancy:</strong> \$10,000 to \$15,000.</li></ul><p>These are respectable numbers. But they’re a far cry from the \$200,000–\$300,000 per month that viral gurus flaunt. And here’s the critical distinction: the creator’s primary income comes from his “school community”—a paid course teaching people how to use NAN (a popular AI automation tool) and build automations. His actual client work is secondary.</p><p>Why does this matter? Because it reveals a pattern. Many of the loudest voices selling “AI agency success” are actually making money by selling the dream, not by delivering automations. They’re in the business of selling shovels during a gold rush, not mining gold themselves.</p><p>If you’re serious about selling AI automations, you need to understand the real economics. Most small businesses won’t pay you \$5,000 a month for a chatbot. They’re used to paying \$50 for a SaaS tool. The gap between what gurus promise and what the market actually bears is enormous.</p><h2 id="why-small-businesses-wont-pay-thousands">Why Small Businesses Won’t Pay You Thousands (Yet)</h2><p>The video creator makes a crucial point: “I guarantee you they are not paying you that much money.” He’s referring to small businesses, which are the target audience for most AI automation agencies.</p><p>Here’s the reality:</p><ul><li><strong>Small businesses have tight budgets.</strong> A local bakery or dental practice isn’t allocating \$10,000 a month for AI. They’re thinking about rent, payroll, and inventory.</li><li><strong>They don’t understand the value yet.</strong> AI automation is still new. Most small business owners don’t know what a “workflow” or “AI agent” is. Selling them requires education, not just a demo.</li><li><strong>Trust is low.</strong> The market is flooded with scammers and overpromisers. Every fake success story makes it harder for honest agencies to close deals.</li></ul><p>Does this mean the opportunity isn’t real? Absolutely not. The AI automation market is massive and growing. But it’s not a get-rich-quick scheme. It’s a legitimate business that requires sales skills, technical expertise, and patience.</p><p>This is where tools like <strong>Dooza.ai</strong> shine. Instead of building custom automations from scratch (which is time-consuming and expensive), Dooza offers pre-built AI employees that handle specific tasks: <strong>Maily</strong> for email management, <strong>Somi</strong> for social media, <strong>Ranky</strong> for SEO, and <strong>Stan</strong> for lead generation. These are ready to deploy, require no coding, and deliver immediate value. For an agency, this means faster onboarding and lower costs. For a business owner, it means predictable results without the headache of hiring a developer.</p><h2 id="the-damage-of-false-claims">The Damage of False Claims: How It Destroys Trust</h2><p>The video creator is visibly frustrated, and for good reason. He says, “It just genuinely hurts people who are trying to jump into this field.”</p><p>Here’s how the lies damage the ecosystem:</p><ul><li><strong>Discouragement:</strong> Honest entrepreneurs watch these videos, try to replicate the results, fail, and give up. They think they’re not good enough, when in reality the numbers were fake.</li><li><strong>Unrealistic expectations:</strong> Clients who’ve seen these claims expect instant, massive ROI. When a legitimate agency delivers a 10x improvement (which is already excellent), the client is disappointed because they expected 100x.</li><li><strong>Market saturation with low-quality providers:</strong> The promise of easy money attracts people with no skills. They flood the market with bad automations, further eroding trust.</li></ul><p>The creator’s advice is simple: “Be careful when you’re watching these videos. They’re lying to you 100%.” He’s not saying the industry is a scam—he’s saying the hype is.</p><p>At <strong>Dooza.ai</strong>, we take a different approach. We don’t promise overnight riches. We promise reliable, specialized AI employees that work 24/7 without breaks. Our AI handles tickets, emails, and customer queries around the clock, so your human team can focus on high-value tasks. No hype, just results.</p><h2 id="what-it-really-takes-to-succeed">What It Really Takes to Succeed in AI Automation</h2><p>If you’re still reading, you’re probably serious about this field. Here’s the honest path to success, based on the video and our own analysis:</p><ol><li><strong>Learn one platform deeply.</strong> The video creator succeeded because he was an early expert in NAN. Pick a platform like Dooza.ai and master it. Understand its capabilities, limitations, and best use cases.</li><li><strong>Focus on a niche.</strong> Don’t try to automate everything for everyone. Pick one industry (e.g., real estate, e-commerce, healthcare) and solve one specific problem (e.g., lead follow-up, appointment scheduling, customer support).</li><li><strong>Build case studies.</strong> Offer your first few clients a steep discount or even free work in exchange for testimonials and permission to share results. Nothing sells like proof.</li><li><strong>Sell value, not features.</strong> Don’t talk about “AI workflows” or “automation triggers.” Talk about saving time, reducing costs, and increasing revenue. Use the language of business outcomes.</li><li><strong>Be patient.</strong> The video creator says it took him a year to build his agency. Expect a similar timeline. The first few months will be slow. That’s normal.</li></ol><p>And if you’re a business owner looking to automate, skip the agency middleman. Go straight to a platform like <strong>Dooza.ai</strong>, where you can deploy AI employees in minutes. <strong>Maily</strong> handles your email inbox, <strong>Somi</strong> manages your social media presence, <strong>Ranky</strong> optimizes your SEO, and <strong>Stan</strong> generates and nurtures leads. They work 24/7, never take breaks, and cost a fraction of a human employee.</p><h2 id="how-dooza-ai-employees-solve-the-real-problem">How Dooza’s AI Employees Solve the Real Problem</h2><p>The video highlights a key tension: businesses want automation, but they don’t want to pay for complex custom solutions. They want something that works out of the box.</p><p>That’s exactly what <strong>Dooza.ai</strong> delivers. Our AI employees are not generic chatbots. They are specialized agents trained for specific roles:</p><ul><li><strong>Maily</strong> – Your AI email assistant. It reads, prioritizes, and responds to emails, handles scheduling, and even drafts complex replies. No more inbox overwhelm.</li><li><strong>Somi</strong> – Your AI social media manager. It creates content, schedules posts, engages with followers, and analyzes performance across platforms.</li><li><strong>Ranky</strong> – Your AI SEO specialist. It audits your site, suggests keywords, optimizes content, and tracks rankings.</li><li><strong>Stan</strong> – Your AI lead generation agent. It identifies prospects, reaches out via email or LinkedIn, qualifies leads, and books meetings.</li></ul><p>These AI employees work 24/7 without breaks, holidays, or sick days. They handle customer queries, support tickets, and repetitive tasks, freeing your human team to focus on strategy and creativity.</p><p>For an agency owner, Dooza is a goldmine. You can white-label our AI employees, offer them as part of your service package, and deliver immediate value without building anything from scratch. For a business owner, it’s the easiest way to start automating without hiring a developer or an agency.</p><h2 id="building-a-sustainable-automation-business">Building a Sustainable Automation Business with Dooza</h2><p>Let’s bring it all together. The video’s core message is that the AI automation industry is real, but the hype is toxic. Success requires hard work, honesty, and the right tools.</p><p>Here’s how you can build a sustainable business using <strong>Dooza.ai</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Start with a niche.</strong> Pick an industry you understand. For example, if you know real estate, offer a package that includes Stan for lead generation and Maily for follow-up.</li><li><strong>Use Dooza as your foundation.</strong> Instead of building custom automations from scratch, leverage our pre-built AI employees. Customize them for your clients’ needs, but don’t reinvent the wheel.</li><li><strong>Focus on support.</strong> One of the biggest pain points for businesses is customer support. Dooza’s AI handles tickets, emails, and queries 24/7. Offer this as a core service.</li><li><strong>Scale with case studies.</strong> Once you’ve delivered results for a few clients, use those case studies to attract higher-paying clients. The proof is in the performance.</li></ul><p>And if you’re a business owner reading this, you don’t need an agency. You can deploy Dooza’s AI employees directly. Book a free consultation to see how Maily, Somi, Ranky, and Stan can transform your operations.</p><h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2><p><strong>Q: Is it really possible to make \$200,000 a month selling AI automations?</strong><br>A: The video creator says it's possible but extremely rare—only about 0.1% of agencies achieve that. Most honest agency owners earn \$10,000–\$30,000 per month after months of hard work. Claims of massive earnings from 18-year-olds are almost always lies.</p><p><strong>Q: Why don't small businesses pay high prices for AI automation?</strong><br>A: Small businesses have tight budgets and often don't understand the value of AI yet. They're used to paying for simple tools, not complex automation systems. Building trust and demonstrating ROI takes time and a consultative sales approach.</p><p><strong>Q: What's the best way to start an AI automation agency?</strong><br>A: Start by learning one platform deeply, like Dooza.ai, which offers pre-built AI employees for email, social media, SEO, and lead generation. Focus on solving one specific problem for a niche market, and build case studies before scaling. Avoid get-rich-quick schemes.</p><p><strong>Q: How can Dooza.ai help me automate my business?</strong><br>A: Dooza.ai provides AI employees that handle specific tasks 24/7: Maily for email management, Somi for social media, Ranky for SEO, and Stan for lead generation. They work without breaks, reducing your workload and freeing you to focus on growth.</p><p><strong>Q: Is the AI automation market a scam?</strong><br>A: No, the market is real and growing. But it's not a lottery. Success requires hard work, honesty, and the right tools. Platforms like Dooza.ai make it easier by providing reliable, specialized AI employees that deliver consistent results.</p><h2 id="cta">Ready to Automate Your Business with AI?</h2><div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1a6b7a, #2a9d5c); border-radius: 16px; padding: 40px; text-align: center; margin: 32px 0;"><h3 style="color: white; font-size: 24px; margin: 0 0 12px;">Ready to automate your business with AI?</h3><p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9); font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 24px;">Book a free consultation with our team and see how Dooza's AI employees can work for you.</p><a href="https://dooza.ai/book" style="display: inline-block; background: white; color: #1a6b7a; padding: 14px 32px; border-radius: 8px; text-decoration: none; font-weight: 700; font-size: 16px;">Book a Free Meeting</a></div>`
