        content: `<h2 id="why-reviewing-matters">Why Reviewing a Real Estate Agent Matters</h2><p>When you're buying or selling a home, the real estate agent you choose can make or break the experience. Learning <strong>how to review a real estate agent</strong> is essential to ensure you partner with someone who truly understands your needs. As Kris Krohn explains in his <em>Real Estate For Beginners</em> video, understanding basic terms like equity, mortgage, and single-family homes is the first step. But beyond vocabulary, you need a systematic method to evaluate an agent's performance, reputation, and fit.</p><p>Many people rush into hiring an agent based on a friend's recommendation or a flashy website. However, a thorough review process can save you thousands of dollars and months of stress. By taking the time to analyze an agent's track record, you protect your investment and increase your chances of a smooth transaction.</p><p>At <a href="/about">Dooza</a>, we believe that AI can help you make smarter decisions. Our AI employees can automate parts of the review process, gathering data from multiple sources and presenting it in an easy-to-digest format. But first, let's cover the fundamentals.</p><h2 id="key-metrics-to-evaluate">Key Metrics to Evaluate an Agent</h2><p>To effectively <strong>review a real estate agent</strong>, you need to look beyond surface-level impressions. Focus on these key metrics:</p><ul><li><strong>Transaction Volume:</strong> How many deals have they closed in the past year? A high volume indicates experience and demand.</li><li><strong>Average Days on Market:</strong> A shorter listing period suggests effective pricing and marketing strategies.</li><li><strong>Sale-to-List Price Ratio:</strong> Agents who consistently sell close to or above the asking price demonstrate strong negotiation skills.</li><li><strong>Client Satisfaction Scores:</strong> Look at online reviews on platforms like Zillow, Realtor.com, and Google. Pay attention to recurring themes.</li><li><strong>Local Market Knowledge:</strong> An agent should know neighborhood trends, school districts, and upcoming developments. Ask them about recent sales in your target area.</li></ul><p>These metrics give you a data-driven foundation. Combine them with personal interviews to get a complete picture. For more tips on evaluating service providers, check out our <a href="/blog">blog</a> for industry insights.</p><h2 id="questions-to-ask-before-hiring">Questions to Ask Before Hiring</h2><p>Once you've gathered initial data, it's time to interview potential agents. Here are essential questions to ask:</p><ol><li><strong>How many homes have you sold in my neighborhood in the last 12 months?</strong> This tests their local expertise.</li><li><strong>What is your marketing strategy for my property?</strong> Look for a mix of online and offline tactics.</li><li><strong>How do you handle multiple offers?</strong> Their approach can affect your final sale price.</li><li><strong>Can you provide references from recent clients?</strong> Speaking directly to past clients gives you unfiltered feedback.</li><li><strong>What are your fees and contract terms?</strong> Understand the commission structure and any cancellation policies.</li></ol><p>Asking these questions helps you gauge their professionalism and whether they align with your goals. Remember, a good agent will welcome your scrutiny. If they seem defensive, consider it a red flag.</p><h2 id="red-flags-to-watch-for">Red Flags to Watch For</h2><p>When you <strong>review a real estate agent</strong>, certain warning signs should prompt you to look elsewhere:</p><ul><li><strong>Lack of Local Knowledge:</strong> If they can't answer basic questions about your area, they likely won't serve you well.</li><li><strong>Poor Communication:</strong> Slow responses or vague answers indicate they may not prioritize your needs.</li><li><strong>Pressure Tactics:</strong> An agent who pushes you to sign quickly or make decisions without full information is not acting in your best interest.</li><li><strong>Negative Reviews:</strong> A pattern of complaints about dishonesty, unavailability, or incompetence is a serious concern.</li><li><strong>Limited Availability:</strong> If they're too busy to meet with you or attend showings, your deal may suffer.</li></ul><p>Trust your instincts. If something feels off, it probably is. Take your time and find an agent who earns your confidence.</p><h2 id="video-guide">Watch: Real Estate Basics for Beginners</h2><p>In this video, Kris Krohn explains fundamental real estate concepts like single-family homes, equity, and mortgages. Understanding these terms will help you better evaluate an agent's expertise and ask informed questions during your review process.</p><div class="not-prose my-8 aspect-video overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 shadow-lg"><iframe class="h-full w-full" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/D69VhdRNok0" title="Real Estate For Beginners" loading="lazy" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe></div><h2 id="using-ai-to-streamline">Using AI to Streamline Your Review Process</h2><p>Manually researching and comparing agents can be time-consuming. That's where AI comes in. With <a href="/features">Dooza's AI employees</a>, you can automate the data collection and analysis stages. For example, an AI agent can:</p><ul><li>Scrape online reviews and ratings from multiple platforms.</li><li>Compile transaction histories and market statistics.</li><li>Generate a comparative report of top agents in your area.</li><li>Schedule interviews and reminders for follow-ups.</li></ul><p>This frees you to focus on the personal connections that matter. AI doesn't replace human judgment, but it makes the process faster and more objective. Ready to try it? <a href="https://accounts.dooza.ai/signup?product=workforce">Sign up for Dooza Workforce today</a> and let AI handle the heavy lifting.</p><p>Additionally, AI can help you monitor an agent's ongoing performance after you've hired them. For instance, you can set up automated check-ins to track progress on showings, offers, and feedback. This ensures you stay informed without constant manual effort.</p><h2 id="final-checklist">Final Checklist for Reviewing a Real Estate Agent</h2><p>Before you make your decision, run through this checklist:</p><ul><li>Verified license and credentials via state database.</li><li>Reviewed at least 10 recent client testimonials.</li><li>Compared transaction volume and sale-to-list ratios.</li><li>Interviewed at least 3 agents with prepared questions.</li><li>Checked for any disciplinary actions or complaints.</li><li>Assessed their marketing plan and technology tools.</li><li>Confirmed availability and communication preferences.</li></ul><p>This checklist ensures you've covered all bases. For a deeper dive into how AI can assist with each step, visit our <a href="/deployment">deployment guide</a>.</p><h2 id="conclusion">Conclusion</h2><p>Knowing <strong>how to review a real estate agent</strong> is a valuable skill that can save you time, money, and stress. By focusing on key metrics, asking the right questions, and watching for red flags, you can find an agent who truly represents your interests. Combine these traditional methods with AI tools like <a href="/pricing">Dooza's AI employees</a> to make the process even more efficient.</p><p>Remember, the goal is not just to find any agent, but to find the right agent for your specific situation. Take your time, do your homework, and don't hesitate to leverage technology. <a href="https://accounts.dooza.ai/signup?product=workforce">Start your free trial with Dooza</a> and see how AI can transform your real estate journey.</p>`
