        content: `<h2 id="what-zia-agents-are">What Zoho Zia Agents Are — and Why People Try Them</h2>
<p>Zoho has spent two decades building one of the broadest software suites in the world, and Zia Agents is the AI layer on top of it. The pitch is genuinely attractive: deploy pre-built agents from Zoho's Agent Store — there are more than a hundred — or assemble your own in the no-code <strong>Zia Agent Studio</strong>, and they will act across the 60+ apps in the Zoho ecosystem. An agent can qualify a lead in Zoho CRM, triage a ticket in Zoho Desk, or chase an invoice in Zoho Books.</p>
<p>If your company already runs end-to-end on Zoho, that is a real capability, and this post will be fair about it: for all-in Zoho shops, Zia Agents are the path of least resistance.</p>
<p>But most businesses are not all-in Zoho shops. And that is where the search for a <strong>Zoho Zia Agents alternative</strong> starts.</p>

<h2 id="where-zia-falls-short">Where Zia Agents Fall Short for Most Businesses</h2>
<p>Talk to teams who trialed suite-native AI agents and the same four frustrations come up again and again.</p>
<h3>1. The agents stop at the edge of the suite</h3>
<p>Zia Agents are built to act inside Zoho apps. But your business almost certainly is not: your email might be Gmail, your store Shopify, your chat WhatsApp and Instagram, your accounting Xero, your calendar Google. A suite-locked agent automates the slice of your operation that lives inside the vendor's walls — and leaves you manually bridging everything outside them. The automation you actually need is the one that crosses those boundaries.</p>
<h3>2. No-code still means do-it-yourself</h3>
<p>Agent Studio removes the code, not the work. Someone on your team still has to design each agent, wire its data sources, write its instructions, test its edge cases, and maintain it when a process changes. For an enterprise with an ops team, fine. For a 5–50 person business, "no-code agent builder" usually translates to a half-configured agent someone abandoned in week three.</p>
<h3>3. An in-app assistant is not an employee</h3>
<p>There is a category difference between an agent that <em>helps inside an app</em> — suggest, summarize, draft — and an AI employee that <em>owns an outcome</em>: the inbox stays handled, the SEO content ships every week, every missed call gets a follow-up, every lead gets a reply in minutes. Zia's agents are bound to app contexts. Outcomes are bound to your business.</p>
<h3>4. The ecosystem is the product</h3>
<p>Zoho's AI strategy exists to deepen your commitment to Zoho — reasonable for them, but it means the more you automate with Zia, the harder it becomes to ever use anything else. Your agents, their training, and your automation logic are only portable within one vendor's universe.</p>

<h2 id="the-dooza-alternative">The Dooza Alternative: AI Employees That Own Outcomes</h2>
<p>Dooza approaches the same problem from the opposite direction. Instead of an agent toolkit bolted onto a suite, <a href="/agents">Dooza gives you a team of AI employees</a>, each owning a business function end-to-end:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Maily</strong> runs your inbox — triage, drafts, replies, and follow-ups that never slip.</li>
<li><strong>Stan</strong> handles sales — lead qualification, instant follow-up, and pipeline nurturing.</li>
<li><strong>Ranky</strong> owns SEO — keyword research, content production, and publishing on schedule.</li>
<li><strong>Somi</strong> runs social — content creation, scheduling, and engagement across platforms.</li>
<li><strong>Rachel</strong> answers your phone — an AI receptionist that handles FAQs and books appointments 24/7.</li>
</ul>
<p>Three structural differences from the Zia model matter most:</p>
<p><strong>Deployment-led, not studio-led.</strong> You do not build these agents in a studio. Dooza's team connects your channels, trains the employees on your business and your tone, sets human-approval rules for anything sensitive, and hands you a working system. The comparison is not "which builder is easier" — it is "builder versus done-for-you."</p>
<p><strong>Works with your real stack.</strong> Dooza's employees plug into the tools you already use — your Gmail, your website, your store, your socials, your phone line. There is no prerequisite to migrate your business onto anyone's suite first.</p>
<p><strong>Your own isolated tenant.</strong> Every Dooza customer runs in a dedicated, isolated environment. Your data, your agents' memory, and everything they learn about your business stays inside your boundary and compounds there — it is yours, not a feature of a suite you are renting.</p>

<h2 id="dooza-workflow">Dooza Workflow: The Automation Canvas Zia Doesn't Have</h2>
<p>The second half of the answer is <a href="/workflow">Dooza Workflow</a> — a visual automation platform where your processes live on a drag-and-drop canvas: triggers, branches, approvals, and connectors for hundreds of apps across your stack.</p>
<p>This is what closes the gap that suite-locked agents leave open. A single Dooza Workflow can catch a new order in your store, check the customer's history, draft the thank-you email through Maily, notify your team in chat, and log everything to your CRM — <em>whichever</em> CRM that is. The workflow crosses vendor boundaries because your business does.</p>
<p>And the two halves compound: AI employees handle the judgment work (reading, writing, deciding, escalating) while Workflow handles the plumbing (triggers, routing, approvals, syncs). Zia Agents gives you agents inside one suite; Dooza gives you the employees <em>and</em> the assembly line underneath them.</p>

<h2 id="comparison-table">Zia Agents vs Dooza: Side by Side</h2>
<div style="overflow-x:auto"><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>Zoho Zia Agents</th><th>Dooza</th></tr></thead><tbody>
<tr><td><strong>Scope</strong></td><td>Agents act inside Zoho's 60+ apps</td><td>AI employees + workflows across your whole stack</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Setup</strong></td><td>DIY in Zia Agent Studio (no-code)</td><td>Deployed and trained for you by Dooza's team</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Model</strong></td><td>In-app agents that assist tasks</td><td>AI employees that own outcomes (inbox, SEO, calls, leads)</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Cross-app automation</strong></td><td>Within the Zoho ecosystem</td><td>Dooza Workflow canvas connects hundreds of apps</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Phone coverage</strong></td><td>—</td><td>Rachel, 24/7 AI receptionist</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Data & learning</strong></td><td>Lives inside your Zoho account</td><td>Isolated per-tenant environment you own</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Best for</strong></td><td>Businesses running 100% on Zoho</td><td>Businesses running on a mixed, real-world stack</td></tr>
</tbody></table></div>

<h2 id="who-should-stay">Who Should Stay on Zia Agents</h2>
<p>Honesty makes comparisons useful: if your business genuinely runs end-to-end on Zoho — CRM, Desk, Books, Mail, all of it — and you have someone who enjoys building and maintaining agents in a studio, Zia Agents are a sensible choice and the deepest Zoho-native option you will find.</p>
<p>Choose Dooza when your stack is mixed, when nobody on the team wants to be the agent-builder, and when what you actually want is not "AI features in my apps" but functions off your plate: support answered, leads followed up, content shipped, calls covered. That is the job AI employees were built for — see how it works for <a href="/blog/automate-customer-support-with-ai">customer support</a>, <a href="/blog/ai-sales-automation-for-small-business">sales</a>, and <a href="/blog/how-we-automate-seo-at-dooza">SEO</a>.</p>
<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1a6b7a, #2a9d5c); border-radius: 16px; padding: 40px; text-align: center; margin: 32px 0;"><h3 style="color: white; font-size: 24px; margin: 0 0 12px;">See your business running on AI employees</h3><p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9); font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 24px;">Book a free setup call — we'll map which functions Dooza's AI employees and Workflow can take off your plate first.</p><a href="https://dooza.ai/book" style="display: inline-block; background: white; color: #1a6b7a; padding: 14px 32px; border-radius: 8px; text-decoration: none; font-weight: 700; font-size: 16px;">Book a Free Setup Call</a></div>

<h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<h3>What is the best Zoho Zia Agents alternative?</h3>
<p>Dooza — AI employees that own whole business functions plus Dooza Workflow for cross-stack automation, deployed for you rather than built in a studio, running in your own isolated tenant.</p>
<h3>What are Zoho Zia Agents?</h3>
<p>Zoho's agentic AI platform: pre-built agents from the Agent Store and a no-code Zia Agent Studio, acting across Zoho's suite of 60+ apps. Strongest for businesses that run entirely on Zoho.</p>
<h3>Why do businesses switch?</h3>
<p>Because their stack is not 100% Zoho, because studio-built agents still need someone to design and maintain them, and because in-app assistance is not the same as owning an outcome.</p>
<h3>Does Dooza work with non-Dooza tools?</h3>
<p>Yes — that is the point. AI employees connect to your real channels, and Dooza Workflow connects hundreds of apps with triggers, branching, and approval steps.</p>
<h3>Is Dooza harder to set up?</h3>
<p>No — Dooza is deployment-led. The team sets up, trains, and tunes your AI employees with you, starting in draft-and-approve mode until accuracy is proven.</p>`
